# Titanic Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

## Objective
To analyze the Titanic dataset and extract insights using visualization and statistics.
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
df = pd.read_csv('titanic.csv')
df.head()
df.info()
df.describe()
df.isnull().sum()
df['Survived'].value_counts()
df['Sex'].value_counts()
df['Age'].fillna(df['Age'].mean(), inplace=True)
df.drop('Cabin', axis=1, inplace=True)
df.dropna(subset=['Embarked'], inplace=True)
sns.countplot(x='Survived', data=df)
plt.title("Survival Count")
plt.show()
More passengers died than survived.
sns.countplot(x='Sex', hue='Survived', data=df)
plt.title("Gender vs Survival")
plt.show()
Females have higher survival rate than males.
df['Age'].hist(bins=30)
plt.title("Age Distribution")
plt.show()
Most passengers are between age 20–40.
sns.boxplot(x='Pclass', y='Fare', data=df)
plt.title("Fare by Passenger Class")
plt.show()
First-class passengers paid higher fares.
sns.heatmap(df.corr(numeric_only=True), annot=True)
plt.title("Correlation Heatmap")
plt.show()
Fare and class show correlation with survival.
sns.pairplot(df)
plt.show()
## Conclusion

- Females had higher survival rates.
- First-class passengers survived more.
- Higher fare increases survival chances.
- Age has moderate impact.

EDA helps in understanding patterns and relationships in data.
